<bdy>

In <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../254/40254.xml">
genetic algorithm</link>s, the term of <b>premature convergence</b> means that a population for an <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../536/1126536.xml">
optimization problem</link> converged too early, resulting in being <link>
suboptimal</link>. In this context, the parental solutions, through the aid of genetic operators, are not able to generate offspring that are superior to their parents. Premature Convergence can happen in case of loss of genetic variation (every individual in the population is identical, see <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../142/1514142.xml">
convergence</link>).
<sec>
<st>
Strategies for preventing premature convergence</st>
<p>

Strategies to regain genetic variation can be:
<list>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 a mating strategy called <it>incest prevention</it><ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%221%22])">1</ref>,</entry>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 <event wordnetid="100029378" confidence="0.8">
<rule wordnetid="105846932" confidence="0.8">
<act wordnetid="100030358" confidence="0.8">
<psychological_feature wordnetid="100023100" confidence="0.8">
<procedure wordnetid="101023820" confidence="0.8">
<activity wordnetid="100407535" confidence="0.8">
<algorithm wordnetid="105847438" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../546/554546.xml#xpointer(//*[./st=%22Uniform+Crossover+and+Half+Uniform+Crossover%22])">
uniform crossover</link></algorithm>
</activity>
</procedure>
</psychological_feature>
</act>
</rule>
</event>
,</entry>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 favored replacement of similar individuals (<it>preselection</it> or <it>crowding</it>),</entry>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 segmentation of individuals of similar fitness (<it>Fitness sharing</it>),</entry>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 increasing population size.</entry>
</list>
</p>

<p>

The genetic variation can also be regained by <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../702/19702.xml">
Mutation</link> though this process is highly random.</p>

